FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>Reply</FONT></A></TD><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT><B><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">Memories</font></B><HR><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">Hey all! Well, fall is in the air … here in Texas as well as Dereth. Being born and raised in Maine I can definitely say that fall was always my favorite season! Cool breezes whipping off the mountains, bright colored leaves of red and gold swirling across the yard, crisp apples plucked from the trees and a variety of vegetables gathered from the late harvest. It seemed almost magic, especially during the nights with that full harvest moon lighting the forests around my parents home in ghostly whites and silvers. My Dad and I use to enjoy long walks together where we wouldn’t say a word … just soak up the magic of the land around us to return home hours later and warm ourselves by a roaring fire. Life was good, but one thing above all others I truly miss … the Saturday night church dinners! All around our community, old, New England, white clabber board churches would hold Saturday night dinners to raise money for church projects and to help the needy. Of all the dishes served … the entire dinner would be judged by the quality of the Bean Hole beans! Now, I’m not sure who came up with the name, but a bean hole supper entailed placing crocks of beans, flavored with maple sugar and fatback, deep into a pit dug in the ground. Next, coals from a wood fire were racked into the pit and covered with damp earth. The beans would slowly bubble and cook deep within the earth all day. When the pits were finally opened that wonderful aroma would waft across the crowds and you just knew you were in for a little scoop of heaven! Now I know down here in Texas they love their ranch style pinto beans, but these beans served way up north where those lovely dark kidney beans … and my personal favorite … the pea bean! I can still taste them now … sitting in the church rectory, surrounded by friends and family, the smell of beans mingling with that of roasted corn, sweet squash, casseroles, steamed lobsters and clams collected from the bay and baking pies. Ahh what a memory! And afterwards, we would sit around and talk about the harvest, the weather and how many fool city foke we had seen tramping through the woods in search of deer and grouse. Of course, while we were sitting there nature would take its course … and now you know why they call the benches in church pews!<br>
<br>
Ok, so why this long dissertation on my childhood? Well, we do happen to have a form of bean in Dereth a brown bean that can be ground into chocolate! So, seeing as its fall, we have beans, and Brocolli Tom, the Emeril Lagausse of the FTFL wants to expand his cooking expertise, I though this weekend sometime we could hold the first annual Bean Race! I propose a contest where we all run off and try to collect as many beans as possible in 1 hour! Now, drudges and mosswarts drop beans so this would mean killing a ton of these critters to get a heap of beans so I would suggest you start looking around the country side to see where the biggest concentration of these critters are to be found. At the end of 1 hour we can all meet back at the tent and count our beans. The winner will receive a nice prize from me…but we all will win because Brocolli Tom will be able to cook some nice chocolate desserts for us! Yum Yum!!<br>
<br>
Let me know what you think!!<br>
</font><P><P><i></i></TD></TR><TR BGCOLOR=#2f2f4f><TD NOWRAP width=20% valign=top align=left><B><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=2><A HREF=http://pub10.ezboard.com/ugharadin.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Gharadin</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_ball.gif BORDER=0 WIDTH=10 HEIGHT=10></FONT></B><BR><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>Registered User</FONT><BR><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>(</FONT><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1 COLOR=#5F9EA0>10/10/00</FONT> <FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1 COLOR=#5F9EA0>11:57:31 am</FONT><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>)<BR></FONT><A HREF=http://pub10.ezboard.com/fforgottentruthforeignlegiongeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=266.topic&index=1><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>Reply</FONT></A></TD><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT><B><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">Re: Memories</font></B><HR><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">What a great description of fall in New England. It's my favorite season too; I think that's true for everyone who grew up in this area. We're having our first real cold snap up here, and the leaves are really starting to turn.<br>
